<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF208-128-884  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 128 884.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEE Proceedings Part E Computers and Digital Techniques  Sept 1989v136 n5 p430(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Detection of stuck-at and bridging faults in Reed-Muller canonical(RMC) networks. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Damarla, T.; Karpovsky, M.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Boolean function realisations by Reed-Muller networks have manydesirable properties in terms of testability.andP;  In this paper it isshown that there exists a single set of test patterns which woulddetect all single stuck-at and all single bridging (short-circuit)faults in Reed-Muller networks, and the number of test patterns isshown to be at most 3n + 5, where n is the number of inputvariables in the function.andP;  In the case of networks with koutputs, where k (is less than or equal to) 2(superscript n), thenumber of test patterns required to detect all single stuck-at andall single detectable bridging faults (both AND and OR) is alsoshown to be 3n + 5.andP;  (Reprinted by permission of the publisher.)andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Boolean AlgebraNetwork ArchitectureTree StructuresMathematics of ComputingNP-Complete ProblemsCanonical FormProblem SolvingCombinational CircuitsTestingCircuit DesignTheoretical ResearchMathematical Models.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Reed-Muller canonical network. (chart)Binary tree generated by test patterns in example. (chart)General structure for multiple output RMC networks. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>